class Solution {
    public boolean canMakeSubsequence(String str1, String str2) {
        int n = str1.length(), m = str2.length();
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while (i < n && j < m) {
            char c1 = str1.charAt(i), c2 = str2.charAt(j);
            if (c1 == c2 || (c1 + 1) % 26 == c2 % 26) {
                j++;
            }
            i++;
        }
        return j == m;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates through str1 and str2 simultaneously, checking if the current character in str1 can be incremented to match the current character in str2. It uses a simple modulo operation to handle the cyclic nature of the alphabet. If all characters in str2 are found in str1 (or can be made to match), it returns true; otherwise, it returns false.
